<Layout>
	<main>
		<BlogContent title = "All about Birds" date = "November 17, 2025">
			<h2> The Wonder of Birds </h2>
			<img src = "../../images/bird1.jpeg">
			<p>
				Birds are some of the most fascinating creatures on Earth. With over 10,000 species, 
				they inhabit every continent, from frozen polar regions to tropical rainforests. Their 
				diversity in size, color, behavior, and song makes them endlessly captivating to humans 
				and a vital part of ecosystems.
			</p>
			<h2> Flight and Adaptations </h2>
			<p>
				Birds are best known for their ability to fly, although not all species do. Their lightweight 
				bones, strong chest muscles, and specialized feathers make flight possible. Birds like hummingbirds 
				can hover mid-air, while albatrosses glide for thousands of miles across oceans. Even flightless birds, 
				such as penguins and ostriches, have unique adaptations for survival in their habitats.
			</p>
			<h2>Communication and Behavior</h2>
			<p>
				Birds communicate in fascinating ways. Songs and calls can attract mates, warn of danger, or establish territory. 
				Many birds are social, forming flocks, cooperating in hunting, or even helping raise each other’s young. Their 
				behaviors reveal intelligence, problem-solving skills, and complex social structures.
			</p>
			<h2>Migration: Nature’s Marathon</h2>
			<p>
				Many birds migrate seasonally, traveling vast distances to find food and suitable breeding grounds. Navigation methods 
				include visual landmarks, the sun and stars, and even Earth’s magnetic field. Migration is one of nature’s most extraordinary 
				feats, showcasing endurance and instinct.
			</p>
			<h2>Birds and Humans</h2>
			<img src = "../../images/bird2.jpeg">
			<p>
				Humans have admired birds for centuries. We keep them as pets, study them scientifically, and enjoy birdwatching. Birds are also 
				crucial to ecosystems, acting as pollinators, seed dispersers, and pest controllers. Conserving bird habitats ensures these benefits 
				continue for generations.
			</p>
		</BlogContent>
	</main>
</Layout>

